# Wangari Maathai — Member Profile
**The Long Council · T1–T5 Knowledge Document**
Framer · Environmental activist and political ecologist · Founder, Green Belt Movement (1977) · Assistant Minister for Environment, Kenya (2003–05) · Member of Parliament for Tetu, Kenya (2003–07) · Professor, University of Nairobi · First African woman and first environmentalist to receive the Nobel Peace Prize (2004)
Born: Nyeri, Kenya, 1 April 1940 · Died: Nairobi, Kenya, 25 September 2011

---

## Doctrine Summary

Wangari Maathai is the theorist and practitioner of the connection between environmental governance, democratic accountability, and women's political agency — the only figure in the council who developed a fully integrated framework linking ecological degradation, authoritarianism, and gender inequality as manifestations of the same underlying problem. Trained as a biologist at the University of Kansas and the University of Pittsburgh, and the first woman in East and Central Africa to earn a PhD (University of Nairobi, 1971), she founded the Green Belt Movement in 1977 — a grassroots tree-planting organisation that became, under conditions of authoritarian rule, a vehicle for civic mobilisation, women's empowerment, and democratic accountability. Her framework rests on a documented three-part analysis: that environmental degradation in post-colonial Africa is not a technical problem but a political one, produced by governance failures that concentrate land, water, and resources in elite hands; that democratic accountability is the precondition for ecological recovery, because communities will only protect what they govern; and that women's empowerment is structurally inseparable from both, because women are the primary users and stewards of the resources most at risk. She spent thirty years building an organisation that had planted more than 51 million trees by her death in 2011, while enduring sustained state harassment under President Daniel arap Moi — including repeated arrests, a near-fatal beating in 1992, and the forcible expulsion of her staff from Uhuru Park during the 1989 protests against a planned 60-storey KANU monument. She is unique in the council for four reasons: she is the only member whose framework is tested in sustained confrontation with a post-colonial African authoritarian regime; the only member who built grassroots institutional infrastructure across three decades under conditions of active state hostility; the only member to integrate environmental, democratic, and feminist analysis into a single operational framework; and the only African woman whose intellectual contribution is grounded in rural development practice rather than diplomatic or academic position. Her framework is directly relevant to 21st-century questions about climate change, land governance, resource extraction in the Global South, the relationship between environmental policy and democratic legitimacy, and the gendered distribution of climate impacts.

